      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was studying for my theory exam and im a bit stuck. can u explain how the circle of fifths works to find the relative major of a key? like if i have eb major, how do i use the circle to find its relative major? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The circle of fifths shows the relationships between keys by moving up or down in perfect fifths. To find the relative major of a given key, you simply move down a minor third (three semitones) from its tonic. Therefore, if you start at E-flat major, moving down a minor third brings you to C minor, which is the relative minor. The key that shares the same relative major/minor relationship is its relative major, so the relative major of C minor is E-flat major.",
